:::summary
Alexander the Great (356–323 BC) was the King of Macedon whose military campaigns created one of the largest empires in ancient history — stretching from Greece to Egypt, Persia, and the borders of India. In just 13 years, he spread Greek language, culture, and philosophy across the known world, creating the Hellenistic world that would become the cultural environment of the New Testament and early Christianity.
:::

